                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d266">
                <head>266. Paper Prepared by <persName corresp="#p_QWB1">William B.
                        Quandt</persName> of the National Security Council Staff<note n="1"
                        type="source" xml:id="d266fn1">Source: National Archives, <persName
                            corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName> Presidential Materials, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files, Box 1279, <persName
                            corresp="#p_SHH1">Saunders</persName> Files, <gloss target="#t_UAR1"
                            >UAR</gloss>, 12/1–12/15/73. Secret; Sensitive. In a covering
                        memorandum, <persName corresp="#p_QWB1">Quandt</persName> asked <persName
                            corresp="#p_SB1">Scowcroft</persName> if the information should be
                        passed on to <persName corresp="#p_SWE1">Simon</persName>. <persName
                            corresp="#p_SB1">Scowcroft</persName> initialed the “no” line. The
                        information was not included in the Presidential briefing material for
                        Saturday, Decmeber 15.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1973-12-14">December 14, 1973</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">PRESIDENT’S SATURDAY BRIEFING</p>
                <p rend="flushleft">For President</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Possible Change in Saudi Oil Policy:</hi> According to the
                    President of <gloss target="#t_ARAMCO1">Aramco</gloss>, Saudi Petroleum Minister
                        <persName corresp="#p_YAZ1">Yamani</persName> has indicated a willingness to
                    modify the oil embargo, even if Saudi Arabia has to act unilaterally without the
                    support of other Arab oil producers. <persName corresp="#p_YAZ1"
                        >Yamani</persName> expressed his desire to find ways to help Belgium, hard
                    hit by the embargo on the Netherlands, and to provide fuel for <gloss
                        target="#t_US1">US</gloss> military forces. Another high Saudi official has
                    concurrently told <gloss target="#t_ARAMCO1">Aramco</gloss> of possible
                    modifications in Saudi oil policy that would permit Arab oil to pass through
                    Rotterdam to other European consumers and through Portland, Maine, for Canadian
                    refineries. If these arrangements are in fact made, <gloss target="#t_ARAMCO1"
                        >Aramco</gloss> would be allowed to increase production to cover these
                    shipments.</p>
                <p>Source: <persName corresp="#p_CJH1">Critchfield</persName> memorandum, December
                    14, 1973<note n="2" xml:id="d266fn2">Not found.</note>
                </p>
            </div>
